Question 1

What are difference(s) between open() and fopen()? Select any which apply.

0 / 1 point
This should not be selected

This statement is true for fopen and not open. Open does not use buffered IO with buffer handling in user space. Buffering for open is handled at the kernel layer, after the syscall interface.

This should not be selected

2.

Question 2

You are working with an application which opened an empty file for reading using:

You've noticed the permissions for the file, as shown by ls -l, are:

-rwxrwx---

What are the reason(s) for this? Select any which may apply.

1 / 1 point
Correct

The three dashes shown at the end of the permissions list from ls -l show that no permissions exist for others or everyone. This is despite the file being created with S_IRWXO which is requesting full read, write, execute permissions for everyone. This behavior is explained by a umask value of 007, which clears read, write and execute bits for others or everyone when creating the file. This umask value must be modified to 0 in order to actually apply the S_IRWXO bits requested in the open function call.

Question 3

Which statements are true about a sparse file with size 10MiB created by opening an empty file, seeking to 10MB past the end of the file, and writing one byte?

1 / 1 point
Correct

The file size displayed by du will be the usage on disk, which does not include the sparse file content. Therefore only the usage on disk, which will be quite small and in the KB range, will be represented in the output.

Correct

The file size displayed by ls will be the size of the file as represented by the filesystem, which includes the sparse file content. Therefore the full size of the file, including sparse content, will be represented in the output.

Question 4

You are writing an application which needs to take input from more than one file descriptor at the same time. What are your implementation options? Select any which apply.

0.5 / 1 point
This should not be selected

If using blocking I/O with a single thread it won’t be possible to support input from more than one file descriptor at the same time. This is because while blocking on one file descriptor any input available on another file descriptor won’t be read.

Correct

The poll() function allows you to watch for input on multiple file descriptors at once. The response will indicate which file descriptor had input available.

Correct

Since threads are dedicated to a file descriptor blocking I/O is acceptable. Multiple file descriptors can be supported at once because each thread will respond when the associated file descriptor has input available.

What would happen if the command below was included in a shell script which was run as the root user and the variable undefined_variable was not defined in the script?

rm -rf /${undefined_variable}

1 / 1 point
Correct

Since ${undefined_variable} would result in an empty response, the equivalent command would be `rm -rf /`, which would attempt to delete the content of the root filesystem.

Correct

12.

Question 12

If errno is set by one thread in a multithreaded program it may be modified by another thread before it is read.

0 / 1 point
Incorrect

Because errno uses thread local storage, the value of errno is actually unique to each individual thread. A modification of errno in one thread does not impact the value read another thread, despite the fact that threads share memory space.

Question 61

Select the types of functions you should avoid calling in a signal handler (select any which apply):

1 / 1 point
Correct

You should avoid accessing global data modified outside the signal handler, since it’s possible a modification to the global data may be in process while the signal handler is executed. Any access to global data within your signal handler needs to be carefully controlled.

Correct

You should avoid calling functions which are not reentrant. If you call a function which is not reentrant, while the function happens to be in the process of being executed in the process, the results may be undefined but could include memory corruption or crashes.

Correct

You should avoid calling functions which are not reentrant, and this includes all functions called from the signal handler. In other words, you must know which functions are called by any functions you call in your signal handler. If you call a function which is not reentrant, while the function happens to be in the process of being executed in the process, the results may be undefined but could include memory corruption or crashes.

66.

Question 66

Race conditions can only occur in programming environments which support parallelism.

1 / 1 point
Correct

Race conditions can also happen with concurrent programming in cases where parallelism isn’t supported or used. Consider a case where a global structure is being modified in one thread, and during modification the thread is swapped with another thread which also modifies the same structure. The result would be a data corruption race condition in an environment which was not using parallelism.
